        notes:
            "Six single-prompt builds of the same game, compared as a Four Quadrants plot: (1) cost, (2) running time, (3) whether the result matches expectation (browser-verified playable build vs. failed/incomplete), and (4) total tokens used (as a proxy for how 'single-prompt clean' the run was — high token counts often mean heavy cache reuse from steering turns or error recovery, not just raw build size). " +
            "Baseline is raw Fable 5 (no skill). Challengers pair a model with the Fabled skill: GLM-5.1 + Fabled on Pi, GLM-5.1 + Fabled on OpenCode, gpt-5.5 + Fabled on Codex, and gpt-5-mini + Fabled on Pi (via GitHub Copilot). Controls isolate the model without Fabled: GLM-5.1 on Pi, the Codex no-skill control, and gpt-5-mini on Pi. " +
            "OpenCode's GLM-5.1 + Fabled run hit a fatal streaming loop and never produced a build (see its REPORT.md) — quadrant 3 = fail, cost/time/tokens not meaningfully comparable. " +
            "gpt-5.5 + Fabled on Codex: $2.87 (196,410 total tokens — 178,037 in · 18,373 out · 1,146,624 cache · 2,625 reasoning), wall-clock not recorded but >=33m56s, delivered a browser-verified build with no console errors — high cost/time, pass. " +
            "The Codex no-skill control: $5.28 (3,019,341 total tokens — 188,004 in · 27,753 out · 2,803,584 cache), 1,243s (~20.7 min) wall time — highest cost of all six, for an unverified/lower-quality result; the skill-equipped Codex run was both cheaper and better. " +
            "gpt-5-mini on Pi (no Fabled, via GitHub Copilot): $0.1615 (2,073,066 total tokens — 118,019 in · 42,087 out · 1,912,960 cache), ~470s active (~7.8 min; ~29.3 min calendar incl. idle browser-testing gaps), took 8 human turns (1 prompt + 5 steering + 2 error reports), and still failed verification — low cost but fail, with heavy human intervention. " +
            "gpt-5-mini + Fabled on Pi: $0.0339 (78,402 total tokens — 16,185 in · 14,345 out · 47,872 cache), ~2.1 min active, 2 prompts (1 original + 1 corrective write), shipped a single-file Three.js game — cheapest and fastest of all six, though Phase 4 was a static trace (Mode A), not a live browser run, so its 'pass' is weaker evidence than the Codex Fabled result. " +
            "Overall pattern: adding Fabled tends to reduce both cost and token count relative to the matching no-skill control for the same model/agent (Codex: $2.87 vs $5.28; gpt-5-mini: $0.034 vs $0.16), while raw model capability still dominates whether the result actually passes (gpt-5.5 passed regardless of skill in this set; gpt-5-mini only shipped something runnable with Fabled's structure).",
